<HL> Your Money Matters:
Old Instruments
Hit Sweet Notes
For Wise Buyers
---
By Julie Amparano
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 02/06/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<TEXT>
   Charles Rudig, director of Sotheby's musical instrument department in New York, scours flea markets, auctions and antique shops for harpsichords, oboes and the like -- for himself and for the company. 
Some of his finds cram his New York apartment and a rented storage room. 

   Among them is a Cramer celesta, an unusual antique English keyboard instrument that produces bell-like tones. 
Mr. Rudig came across the celesta on an outing in 1980. 
"I just had to have it," he says. 
He paid $500 for it. 
The instrument was recently appraised at $2,000. 

   For the right kind of investor, musical instruments offer the possibility of good returns -- and, perhaps, more tangible enjoyment than securities in a safe-deposit box. 
But investment advisers caution that the field isn't for those without expertise or substantial resources. 

   James D. Koster, an investment adviser in Tucson, Ariz, says that while musical instruments can appreciate rapidly, they can be difficult investments. 
As with other collectibles, liquidity is a problem: If a need for cash arises, it may be difficult to find a buyer quickly for an antique instrument. 
And unlike a block of stock, "you can't sell a little piece of a violin. 
You have to sell the whole thing." 
Also, some instruments require special maintenance. 

   Investors shouldn't tie up more than 15% of their assets in instruments, Mr. Koster says. 
But despite the limitations, he says, instruments offer a "very exciting investment with high appreciation." 

   Many appraisers, however, expect appreciation in the coming decade to fall short of the gains of the past 20 years. 
While the future of any collectible market is hard to predict, appraisers say they expect antique instruments generally to double in value over the next decade. 
At the start of the boom 20 years ago, prices of some instruments rose ten-fold in about three years. 
Since then, prices generally have doubled about every five years. 

   The spurt has been fueled by investors who earlier concentrated on paintings and sculpture, says Mr. Rudig of Sotheby's. 
These investors came to view antique instruments as works of art with musical value, he says. 
As with many other collectibles, the rapid inflation of the 1970s boosted values. 
Changing musical tastes also have played a part: More and more orchestral musicians are seeking an antique sound they can only get from older instruments, he says. 

   Potential investors who aren't expert in the field should have instruments appraised before buying them, says Fred W. Oster, an official in Christie's musical instrument department. 
A hairline crack in the wrong place, he says, can be enough to make an instrument virtually worthless. 

   One basic rule: An instrument that can't be played isn't worth much. 
A St. Louis investor paid $500 for a vintage flute, then discovered that it made only a honking sound. 
To date, he hasn't been offered more than $100 for it. 

   In general, specialists say, the most lucrative instruments are antique strings -- violins, violas and cellos. 
Buying this kind of fine antique involves little risk, they say. 
Violins are considered the most valuable member of this group; their rate of appreciation is highest. 
A Stradivarius that sold 20 years ago for about $40,000 now commands more than $400,000. 

   More modest investments are available in antique woodwinds, like flutes, oboes and recorders. 
Sydney G. Rosenblatt of Philadelphia sold a Haynes flute last December for about $3,500. 
While he won't disclose his profit, he says the item would have brought about $1,500 a decade ago. 
But woodwinds involve more risk than string instruments, because their prices haven't been as long established. 

   Michael Sweeney, who owns a piano store in Philadelphia, says American pianos built between the turn of the century and the Depression have become collectibles. 
Marilyn Gushner, a housewife in Gladwyne, Pa., bought a 1924 Cunningham player piano four years ago for $3,600 while it was "still in a million pieces." 
She recently had it appraised at $6,000. 

   The instruments of famous musicians, even if not antiques, can draw hefty prices. 
Efrem Kurtz, a conductor, reaped a windfall when he auctioned off a platinum flute that had belonged to one of America's greatest flutists, William Kincaid. 
Last October, at Christie's in New York, the flute brought $187,000, the highest price ever recorded for a woodwind instrument. 

</TEXT>
