   FIDDLE RIDDLE: Is there life after 250 for a Stradivarius? 

   Musician Louis A. Browning of Portland, Ore., paid $130,000 for a Stradivarius made in 1736, $27,000 for a 1779 Gabbrielli, and $24,000 for a 1675 Ruggeri. 
He sought to depreciate them over 12 years, to the tune of more than $15,000 a year in deductions. 
But the IRS denied the deductions, challenging the 12-year-useful-life forecast as too short and arguing that the rare violins' "salvage" value would rise, not fall to zero. 
So Browning appealed to the Tax Court. 

   Browning, backed by a dealer, said the Strad ("not a prime specimen") and its value would deteriorate with use. 
Yet the dealer had appraised it for insurance at $225,000 five years after selling it to Browning and wouldn't speculate on the value after 12 years. 
Judge Hamblen found no evidence that the Strad would be worthless after 12 years or that its useful life would end at that point. 
Browning offered no direct evidence relating to the other two violins. 

   Browning's claims were "arbitrary and unreasonable," the judge said in upholding the IRS. 

   THIS IRA CHECK missed the trick: It bounced instead of rolling over. 

   You may withdraw cash temporarily from an individual retirement account and escape a tax or penalty, if you roll it all over into another IRA in 60 days. 
That's a rigid "if," as a chap we'll call Chip found. 
He took cash from an IRA at one bank last Aug. 14 and wrote a check on Oct. 7 for a rollover IRA at another. 
He drew the check on yet a third bank, where a clerical error had restricted his account's credit. 

   Chip's check bounced. 
After clearing up the snafu, he wrote a new check on Oct. 28 -- two weeks after the 60-day deadline -- that set up a new IRA on Nov. 2. 
The delay wasn't my fault, he told the IRS, so I should be allowed a rollover. 
Not so, says IRS private ruling 8824047: Tax law and regulations don't permit any waivers or extensions of the 60-day period. 
Chip's transaction fails to qualify as an IRA rollover. 

   EQUITY BEATS OUT consistency in handling disgorged profits, it appears. 

   Last week, U.S. Judge Owen in New York denied requests by insider-trader Dennis Levine and conspirator Robert Wilkis to pay back taxes out of disgorged profits, not other resources. 
The profits are to be held in trust "for the benefit of defrauded investors," the judge ruled. 
Yet in October, Owen had granted the similar requests of ring members Ira B. Sokolow and David S. Brown. 
So lawyers for Levine and Wilkis denounced the unfavorable inconsistency. 

   What's going on? 
Owen's rulings don't address consistency directly, but suggest it's irrelevant. 
Tax claims may be paid at the court's "equitable discretion," he wrote in October; he considered the defendants' roles in the conspiracy, the amounts of their profits, and other factors. 
As to ringleader Levine and Wilkis, he wrote last week, the courts "have general equity powers to remedy violations of the securities laws and to fashion appropriate remedies." 

   The IRS, eager for its share, hasn't indicated whether it will appeal the latest ruling. 

   I WON'T PAY the $60 filing fee or show I can't pay, Bruce Charles Frazier of Pasadena, Calif., told the Tax Court in appealing an IRS bill; he wanted a waiver for raising a constitutional issue. 
But for not paying, the court has dismissed his claims; it also upheld a civil fraud penalty. 

   EMPLOYERS now are liable for Social Security tax on unreported tip income uncovered in audits of employees. 
An employer can set up a reserve for that contingency; but doing it may look like an admission of incorrect tip reporting, warns David J. Silverman, a New York tax adviser. 

   WAYS AND MEANS adds Clay Shaw (R., Fla.) to fill a vacancy caused by the death of the House committee's ranking minority member, John Duncan (R., Tenn.). 
Bill Archer of Texas succeeded Duncan as the committee's ranking Republican member. 

   MORTGAGE SUBSIDIES would be targeted to more of the needy. 

   State and local authority to sell exempt bonds to finance low-interest mortgages for first-home buyers expires Dec. 31. 
Tax-bill writers propose to extend it through 1990 and to tighten eligibility in response to critics and suggestions from the General Accounting Office, which has questioned the efficacy of the subsidies. 
The aim is to get aid to the needy and exclude many families that can afford market-rate mortgages. 

   The bill doesn't go as far as the GAO would. 
But it would lower the income ceiling for childless families, giving an advantage to parents. 
It would adjust income limits in areas where housing costs are very high or very low in relation to income. 
And as people tend to sell homes when their incomes rise, it would reward long-term possession: Generally, the government would recapture all or part of the subsidy from a homeowner who sold within 10 years. 

   Among other things, the GAO suggested limiting aid to parents over the age of 30. 

   BRIEFS: Just out are reporting requirements for the Social Security tax on employer-paid premiums for group term life insurance; see IRS Notice 88-82. . . . 
The IRS could reduce futile investigations of nonfiling businesses by eliminating duplicate identification numbers, publicizing the need to file quarterly employment-tax returns, and updating its records more accurately with the results of its investigations, the General Accounting Office says. 

