<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS: TV Preview: Lincoln, Darrow, Dickens, Rumpole </HL>
<AUTHOR> Martha Bayles </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<TEXT>
   Thursday, March 17, 8-9 p.m. EST, on PBS (PBS dates and times vary, especially during this "Festival," or pledge-drive period, so check local listings): "Stradivarius on Stage." 
Great musicians and rare instruments come together for a tribute to Antonio Stradivari, the 17th-century master craftsman whose violins and cellos still inspire awe. 

   Thursday, March 17, 9-10 p.m. EST, on A&amp;E (repeated at 1 a.m. and on Mar. 20): "Galway and the Chieftains in Belfast." 
Instead of chugging lime-green beer, celebrate St. Patrick's Day by listening to James Galway's brilliant flute and the authentic sounds of Ireland's best-known traditional band. 

   Thursdays, March 17-April 21, 9-10 p.m. EST, on PBS: "Rumpole of the Bailey." 
Due to popular demand, "Mystery!" is bringing back Leo McKern for another round of gruff, eccentric litigation in London's Old Bailey. 

   Sunday, March 20, 7-8 p.m. EST, on Cinemax (repeated on March 22, 24 and 30): "Cinemax Sessions: A Reggae Session." 
If you've missed these excellent music specials, you're in luck this month. 
Along with this new one, featuring reggae stars Jimmy Cliff, Toots Hilbert and members of the late Bob Marley's family and band, Cinemax also is repeating all nine previous "Sessions." 

   Sunday, March 20, 9-11 p.m. EST, on NBC: "Inherit the Wind." 
A new TV version of the famous play about the 1925 Scopes trial stars Jason Robards as the Clarence Darrow character and Kirk Douglas as the William Jennings Bryan character. 
Tune in and judge for yourself whether this AT&amp;T-sponsored production has monkeyed around with the original. 

   Sunday, March 20, 9-11 p.m.; Monday, March 21, 8:05-11:05 p.m.; and Tuesday, March 22, 8:05-10:05 p.m. (all times EST); on SuperStation TBS (repeated March 29-31 and April 10, 17 and 24): "Portrait of the Soviet Union." 
From Ted Turner and Britain's Antelope Films come seven hours of free travel from Chernobyl to Tbilisi to Lake Baikal, stunningly photographed but ineptly narrated. 
More in Monday's column. 

   Saturday, March 26, 4-6 p.m. and Sunday, March 27, 2-6 p.m. EST, on NBC: The Players Championship. 
After several years of appearing on CBS, this super-duper golf tournament has passed into the capable hands of NBC Sports. 
From Sawgrass in Ponte Verde, Fla., Sandy Lyle will defend his trophy. 

   Saturday, March 26, 8-9:45 p.m. EST, on HBO (repeated on April 3, 6, 9 and 15): "The Tracker." 
After a couple of disastrous recent roles (including in ABC's "Amerika"), Kris Kristofferson is perfect as a retired Indian tracker pressed into service by his old friend the marshal (David Huddleston) to chase a murdering, kidnapping religious fanatic across the spectacular landscape of Arizona and New Mexico. 
Along for the ride is the tracker's Eastern-educated son (Mark Moses), who scorns, but then adopts, his father's stern frontier code. 
Don't miss this handsome, no-nonsense, no-spaghetti western. 

   Sunday and Monday, March 27 and 28, 9-11 p.m. EST, on NBC: "Gore Vidal's Lincoln." 
No, this title doesn't refer to an automobile belonging to Mr. Vidal; it is television's way of identifying author and best seller in the same breath. 
Sam Waterston stars as Abraham Lincoln, who's trying simultaneously to preserve the Union and his marriage to Mary Todd Lincoln (Mary Tyler Moore). 

   Sunday, March 27, 9-11 p.m. EST, on CBS: "Too Young the Hero." 
The average age of American soldiers in World War II was 26, yet there were some youngsters fighting. 
Calvin Graham, for example, enlisted in the Navy at 12 and became a hero nominated for the Bronze Star, only to be tossed into the brig for lying about his age. 
The real Mr. Graham visited the production on location aboard the USS North Carolina and pronounced it accurate. 

   Sundays, March 27-April 24, 9-10 p.m. EST, on PBS: "David Copperfield." 
When Charles Dickens was 12, his parents sent him to work in a shoe-polish factory. 
Out of that experience came his much-adapted autobiographical novel about growing up in the rigid class system of Victorian England, here adapted one more time for "Masterpiece Theatre." 

   Tuesday, March 29, 9-10 p.m. EST, on PBS: "Back in the U.S.S.R." 
Former Time magazine correspondent Jerry Schecter returns to Moscow after 20 years, to size up glasnost for himself. 
More in Monday's column. 

</TEXT>
