<HEAD>Sword, Rare Violins Among Stolen Antiques Found</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators say they have recovered more
than $500,000 in stolen antiques _ including two centuries-old
violins and a sword reportedly used by Civil War General William T.
Sherman.
   The merchandise, which also included books, coin collections,
toy cars and guns, was found Thursday in a storage locker.
   ``We're saying half-a-million dollars right now, but that's
probably a very conservative estimate,'' said Dennis Palmentera, an
investigator with the Ohio Organized Crime Investigation Commission.
   Police have arrested 29 people since a grand jury in Columbus,
Ohio, returned secret indictments Jan. 2 in connection with an
Ohio-based burglary ring, but no arrests have been made involving
the Savannah cache.
   Investigators say the ring has operated for 20 years and is
blamed for more than $1.8 million in thefts over five years.
   ``The ring had fingered out from Ohio,'' said Harold Crabtree,
also an investigator with the Ohio task force. ``It spread from
Ohio to Florida and was in every state in between.''
   The Sherman-related items, which included a portrait of the
Union general, were stolen from Sherman's birthplace museum in
Lancaster, Ohio, investigators said.
   The violins were believed made by Antonio Stradivari, the famous
Italian craftsman.
   Palmentera said investigators believe the antiques stashed in
Savannah were destined for a major antiques show in Norcross.
   ``They store it for six months or a year until it cools off,
then they'd sell it,'' Palmentera said. ``They sell it in the major
shows because this stuff is hard to track.''
</TEXT>
