<HEAD>Two Valuable Italian Violins Stolen at Tokyo University</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Italian violins, together worth more than
$130,000, were stolen from practice rooms of a university during
the past two weeks, police said Sunday.
   Police said they suspected people associated with the university
committed the separate thefts at the Tokyo National University Of
Fine Arts and Music.
   A police spokesman said a student left her $26,600 violin on a
table in a practice room Friday, and instrument was gone when she
returned 90 minutes later.
   Another student left her $106,400 violin in a practice room on
June 5 for a five-minute trip to the bathroom but found it gone
upon her return, police said. Her violin was crafted by Joannes
Gagliano of Italy in 1803, police said.
</TEXT>
