<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
Feting Slava and His 'Wooden Wife'
---
By Heidi Waleson</HL>
<DD> 02/23/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Up close and personal, Mstislav Rostropovich seems a little shy and frail, wisps of white hair clinging to his head as he walks slowly, almost timidly, onto the Carnegie Hall stage to conduct the National Symphony in a brief rehearsal before the 8 p.m. concert. 

   He looks closer to 70, but March 27 is his 60th birthday, and his management has organized a marathon birthday celebration for him here: 18 concerts between Feb. 6 and March 24, including 10 different programs, 15 cello concertos, two solo recitals of Bach suites and three programs for which he is conductor, including the War Requiem of Benjamin Britten with the New York Philharmonic and his wife, soprano Galina Vishnevskaya, as one of the soloists. 

   All this will be capped by a gala at the Kennedy Center in Washington on the birthday itself. 
Among the onstage revellers: Leonard Bernstein, Jean-Pierre Rampal, Isaac Stern, Yehudi Menuhin. 

   One of the effects of all this mellifluous frenzy will be to allay any suspicions that "Slava" Rostropovich, one of the world's most celebrated cellists, is thinking about giving up his instrument for conducting, now that he has been music director of the National Symphony for 10 years, and is recording operas. 
Forget it. 
The "wooden wife," as he calls his Stradivarius, is not about to become a silent partner. 

   Cellist, pianist, conductor Rostropovich says that he is a "musician" first. 
He talks fast, starting off in English, then falling into Russian, then back again. 
Is he a cellist by accident? 
"I am a human being by accident! 
The result of love between my mother and father! 
My father gave me a cello and said 'Play.' 
If he had given me a violin, I probably would have tried to play the violin. 
But I'm happy I play the cello. 
I love the instrument very much." 

   The first pair of concerts, with the National Symphony, had Mr. Rostropovich conducting the first evening and playing three cello concertos the next. 
Hugh Wolf, his conducting protege and now music director of the New Jersey Symphony, did the conducting honors on the second night. 
It was a mix of the familiar and the unfamiliar, as are most of the rest of these programs: the war horse Schumann Cello Concerto in A minor, with its hazardous pianissimo balances between cello and orchestra; Bloch's schmaltzy Schelomo, which gave Mr. Rostropovich the opportunity to emote in long lines and to emit powerful, growling low notes. 

   Both orchestra and soloist sounded tentative in the beginning of the Schumann; more expansive by its slow middle movement. 
Still, for the first half of the program Mr. Rostropovich seemed to be on automatic pilot. 

   Not so for the second half, Henri Dutilleux's "Tout un Monde Lointain." 
This imagistic, very French score took off with Mr. Rostropovich showing off all the cello's incarnations: the very high register, the double stops, the long singing notes. 
And the orchestra went from the mysterious eccentricities of the opening to the colors dissolving into cacophony at the end. 
It was a thrill, and everyone in the audience felt it. 
Mr. Rostropovich practically dragged the composer up onto the stage for a bow. 

   Let that be a lesson to the orchestra managers who insist on the standard repertoire when they engage Mr. Rostropovich -- and that's most of them. 
He won't admit that he's bored with the standard cello rep -- Dvorak, Strauss, Tchaikovsky -- but it sure sounds like it. 
"When orchestras invite for the Dvorak concerto, the concert hall is immediately sold out. 
Also some conductors like, in rehearsal, to spend time on the symphony, not the accompaniment for cello. 
Dvorak is much easier than a new piece." 

   Mr. Rostropovich has their number, however. 
"I'm going to make a new condition. 
When I go to play, I will play one new piece and one classical." 
Will the orchestras agree? 
"I don't know. 
But I have many engagements, so I have choices." 

   For his own party, however, Mr. Rostropovich has decided what the music is going to be, and maybe all those orchestra managers should come and check it out. 
The cello concertos include the Penderecki No. 2 (1982), the Lutoslawski (1970) and the Dutilleux (1970), all of which were dedicated to him, and which he has never before played in New York. (The latter two can be heard on Angel S-37146; Mr. Rostropovich has recorded most of the standard repertoire for cello, and a fair amount of Russian symphonic music -- as a conductor, too.) 

   There are works by his friends Prokofiev, Shostakovich and Britten, also dedicated to him. 
And there is "Three Meditations for Mass," arranged especially for Mr. Rostropovich by his friend Mr. Bernstein, who was instrumental in getting him out of the Soviet Union back in 1974. 
That was after the Soviet government had derailed the cellist's career, because of a letter he wrote in defense of Alexander Solzhenitsyn. 

   "They are pieces that are representative of different times in my life, " Mr. Rostropovich says. 

   Except for the Penderecki, he plans to play all the cello pieces from memory. 
"I have never worked as hard or as much on the cello as I have in this period. 
The Dutilleux is extremely difficult, and I didn't make any mistakes there!" he says proudly. 
"The Britten cello symphony I haven't played for 20 years, so it is like a new composition. 
And after 20 years, I see other sides of the piece." 

   And after 13 years in the West, Mr. Rostropovich has plenty of money, too, including a hefty income ($606,250 in 1984-85 for his labors for the debt-ridden National Symphony; and, reportedly, one of the world's higher soloist fees). 
He divides his engagements -- between 100 and 140 a year -- equally between cello playing and conducting. 
Ensconced at the orchestra in D.C. (although he actually lives in Paris and travels on a Swiss passport), he is a symbol of American moral superiority on the issue of human rights. 
Fortunately, he's also a pretty fair conductor, as his new recording of Tchaikovsky's opera "Yolanta" on Erato attests. 

   As for going back to visit the country that stripped him and his wife of their citizenship in 1978, he says he hasn't been officially invited, as some other Soviet emigre artists have, and isn't sure what he'd do if he were. 

   Perhaps Mr. Gorbachev doesn't want to interrupt the superb job Mr. Rostropovich is doing as an interpreter of Shostakovich to Western ears, both in music and in words. 
"Shostakovich," he says, jumping happily into a favorite topic, "is our contemporary composer; he is speaking about our life, all our emotion, stress, deep depression, emotional explosion; that's the music of Shostakovich. 
It's a mirror of us." 

   It definitely looks as if there will be more work for Mr. Rostropovich's wooden wife after the birthday fuss is over. 
The non-wooden wife, he says, "is not jealous." 

   ---
   Ms. Waleson is a New York free-lancer who writes frequently about music. 

</TEXT>
</DOC>

