<TEXT>
   
   ``Popular Songs and Irish Ballads'' (EMI) _ John McCormack
   
   John McCormack made his opera and recording debut in 1904 at age
21. He left the opera stage 19 years later but continued making
records and recital appearances for two more decades. Along the
way, he became one of the concert world's first true superstars, a
stage idol who collected million-dollar salaries, race horses,
homes and old master paintings, but who never lost his feel for the
popular music his concert audiences loved.
   This son of Ireland, though a terrible opera actor, was a
tremendous artist whose vocal glory was renowned. It was the great
violinist Fritz Kreisler, or in some versions Jan Kubelik, who said
McCormack had a Stradivarius in his throat. Sounds, beautiful
sounds, poured out effortlessly.
   This EMI rerelease under the series ``Great Recordings of the
Century'' (an odd title, since records haven't been made in any
other century) presents the songs that his mass public loved, and
that McCormack loved to sing. They range from 1930 to 1941, with
one from 1908. The incomparable accompanist Gerald Moore appears on
11 tracks.
   The listener must have a bent for Irish ballads, or surrender
him or herself to the period sentimentality of the music, to enjoy
this disc. If either is the case, it can only delight.
   The extremely generous program _ 23 songs at 73:03 _ gives the
range of the popular-music McCormack. ``The Garden Where the
Praties Grow'' is a typical, light-hearted ditty of the Old Sod.
McCormack sings a melancholy ballad of parting in ``Terence's
Farewell to Kathleen.'' In the charming ``Off to Philadelphia,''
the tenor is the happy-go-lucky immigrant who ``lately took the
notion for to cross the briny ocean.''
   A more perfect interpretation of ``Jeanie With the Light Brown
Hair'' could not be imagined. McCormack's voice here resembles a
line from this favorite: ``floating like a vapor on the soft summer
air.''
   A sad story about McCormack, who died in 1945, is told by Henry
Pleasants in his book ``The Great Singers'': ``Towards the end of
his life, when nothing but the records was left, he would play them
again and again, exclaiming happily, and a bit wistfully _ possibly
a bit incredulously: `I was a damned good singer, wasn't I?'''
   He was. Even in the recordings made in his mid-50s, the timeless
McCormack sounds like a brave lad about to step ashore in America,
or the young wooer of a sweet colleen.
   _ By Daniel J. Wakin, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Good Evening'' (Warner Bros.) _ Marshall Crenshaw
   
   Singer-songwriter Marshall Crenshaw's bright and bouncy
guitar-based tunes seem ready-made for the Top 40. But seven years
after the release of a stunning debut album, he's still looking for
a commercial breakthrough.
   So on ``Good Evening,'' Crenshaw turns to outside sources for
half of the 10 songs. The result is some of his best performances
yet _ Richard Thompson's ``Valerie,'' Bobby Fuller's ``Let Her
Dance'' and John Hiatt's ``Someplace Where Love Can't Find Me.''
Crenshaw's own songs are strong, too, especially the lovely ``She
Hates to Go Home.''
   But artistically, Crenshaw's problem has been the way he is
recorded, rather than his material. Crenshaw albums usually sound
as though something is wrong with the stereo.
   That hasn't changed on ``Good Evening.'' Instead of a clean,
sparse texture that would serve these hook-filled pop songs best,
Crenshaw opts for a dense, sometimes muddy sound. The blatting bass
and hissing cymbals mar an otherwise fine record.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
