<DESCRIPT>  MUSIC; EQUIPMENT; REPAIR; BUSINESS; JAPANESE-US; SAN-JOSE; PROFILE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The smell of freshly cut wood welcomes new visitors inside Hideo Kamimoto's
small shop even before a wall lined with at least 80 multisized violins meets
the eye.;    The workshop, in the rear, is a familiar sight to regular
customers who enter and leave through the back door.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  East Extra  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FINE-TUNING THE VIOLIN BUSINESS
MEN FORM DUET TO SERVE MUSICIANS, YOUNG AND
OLD  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Also ran in EX1/6, EX4/1  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     At the counter, between the workshop and the violin wall, Kamimoto speaks
to a customer preparing to leave with his treasured instrument.;    The sound
of sanding coming from the rear stops, and a man's voice calls out a
farewell.;    Kamimoto opened Kamimoto String Instruments 10 months ago at 609
N. Fourth St. in Japantown. The self-taught violin and guitar repairman runs
the shop.;    Scott Shu-Kun Cao, Kamimoto's partner of nearly six months,
specializes in making and repairing violins and other string instruments, such
as the cello and viola.;    "You could say I learned as an apprentice,"
Kamimoto said. "I had no formal background like Scott did. I worked part-time
for repair shops when I went to Cal (University of California, Berkeley).;   
"I got interested in the guitar and how it was made after I was folk singing
for a while in college.;    "There are no standards to guitar repair, there
still aren't. In 1975, I wrote a book ("Complete Guitar Repair"). Now, it's a
standard text.";    Kamimoto and Cao joined forces in January. "Scott was
working in a violin shop in Berkeley where I bought instruments. I met him
there. We got to talking," Kamimoto said.;    "We thought that by the two of
us getting together, we could strengthen our position in the field.;   
"Together, we improved our customer service by providing a wider range of
services, and we have expanded beyond San Jose to a wider retail area," he
added.;    Aside from repairing string instruments, Kamimoto also imports
Chinese violins used by professional musicians.;    "These violins are of the
highest quality," he said. "They are hand-crafted and equal the value of those
from even Germany. They, of course, cost a lot less because of the current
working conditions in China.";    Cao is originally from China, and had two
years of formal training in violin-making there. After graduating, he went to
work at Kapok, a renowned violin factory in China.;    He moved to the United
States seven years ago. In San Francisco, Cao worked at Rolland Feller's
violin shop, where he received his violin-repair training. He also worked for
Ifshin, a violin shop in Berkeley.;    "I was the major repairman there at
Ifshin, and in my spare time I kept making violins," Cao said. "In 1988, I was
given the chance to attend a violin workshop, where I was taught by famous
violin makers like Hans Weisshaar and Luiz Bellini.";    Now with Kamimoto,
Cao specializes in restoring string instruments.;    The shop also sells
materials to students of the Suzuki Instructional Method, which teaches
childrento play instruments at a very early age.;    "The theory of this
method is based on the fact that children learn through imitation, just like
they learn to speak long before they can read and write," Kamimoto said.;   
Similarly, Suzuki students listen to recorded music while learning to play.;  
 Kamimoto provides the instruments, tapes and books necessary to start young
children on the violin and cello.;    The instruments for the Suzuki method
are specially crafted for young children as they grow.;    A typical
3-year-old starting on the Suzuki method will go through six sizes of violins
before playing the standard-sized instrument.;    The smallest violin, 14 1/2
inches, looks toy-like compared with the standard-sized ones hanging on the
front wall. Kamimoto said it was not a toy, but was made to fit a 3-year-old's
arm.;    Kamimoto and Cao have customers from all over the globe. Their
regular Californian customers come from as far as the East Bay and even Los
Angeles.;    Both said they see strong support for the fine arts from the
Asian community.;    "There is a large group of Asians, mainly Koreans,
Chinese and Japanese, who choose to start their 3- or 4-year old children on
playing string instruments," Cao said. "These children grow up with the
violin, cello or viola, and they need good professional service to keep up
their instruments.;    "And when these students take that next step on
becoming professionals, they need a shop that provides quality instruments. We
provide these services to our customers."  </TEXT>
