<HL> Chain-Saw Massacre: Finger Lakes Slashes Its Way to Victory --- College Woodsmen Despoil Trees in Name of Sport; Eat Wood, Lumberhead! </HL>
<AUTHOR> David Stipp (WSJ Staff) </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<DATELINE> WATERVILLE, Maine  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Okay, sports-trivia buffs, show your stuff: In the twitch-peavey-deck, does the scoot load come first or last? 

   Hint: We're talking about a sport in which frying pans are standard equipment, Community College of the Finger Lakes in New York state is top-seeded, and boiling water is a competitive event. 

   Stumped? 
You're getting warmer. 

   The twitch-peavey-deck is part of the Woodsmen's Weekend, an annual intercollegiate contest in which enthusiastic young people do violence to trees. 

   The 42nd such contest, held here at Colby College last weekend, attracted some 40 men's and women's six-member teams from schools in the Northeast U.S. and Canada. 
They spent two days chopping, sawing and otherwise trying to clear-cut the competition at traditional lumberjack skills. 
It was the Rose Bowl of the woodsmen's world, but you probably didn't hear about it. 

   Although the sport has all the ebullient bloodletting of rugby, it remains well out on the periphery of American athletics. 
Even at forestry schools there's limited interest in lugging logs across muddy fields in driving sleet, as one event calls for, to say nothing of standing around watching others do it. 
And the sport's heroes, though hard as a sack of hammers, don't have much TV appeal: "They say it's a sport for old, fat men," says Don Quigley, a husky 39-year-old who teaches forestry at the University of New Hampshire and competes on the pro circuit. 

   Still, it is the rodeo of the plaid-shirt-and-gum-boots crowd, including the ones from Brooklyn and Berkeley. 
When the gleaming "racing" axes and lovingly tended $1,500 competition saws are brought out, the adrenalin rises like sap in April. 

   "Eat wood!" screams Colby captain Jeff Glover, as his teammates rip through a timber with a two-handled saw in an event called "crosscut from hell." 
Describing another event, in which competitors stand on elevated logs while chopping them in two, Colby woodsmen's coach Debbie Smith says, "People love to see people chopping at their feet." 

   It is considered bad form to fell trees on opposing teams, but just about anything else in lumberjack lore is fair game at collegiate woodsmen's meets. 
Competitive tobacco spitting is a disgusting old favorite, and many contestants here constantly warmed up for it even though, this time, it wasn't on the program. 
Lately, lighting matches with ax blows is in fashion. 

   The host team for a meet can customize the events or even spring new ones on opponents. 
Two years ago, a Canadian host team stunned rivals with a new event for which it had practiced for months. 
The idea: to knock an opponent off logs spinning on ball bearings. 
Another host school introduced fly-casting at inner-tube targets, but strong winds blew away its advantage. 

   At the Colby meet, participants race canoes, throw axes, lob logs, fell trees, clamber up poles and scramble through the woods with packs containing 50-pound weights and a skillet. 
The water-boil race involves building a fire and boiling water, using only three matches, one log and various sharp tools. 
In the twitch-peavey-deck, two people twitch, or drag, a 400-pound log with ropes. 
Then, using peaveys -- harpoonlike tools -- they roll it through an obstacle course. 
And finally, they scoot the whole load up a ramp, called a deck. 

   All this is considered great fun by these amateur woodsmen, who relish the camaraderie that develops among people sharing pain. 
Their meets have little to do with modern logging, in which people in air-conditioned cabs often dismantle trees with huge machines. 
But the sport includes oddball concessions to modern realities, like the chain-saw log-cutting competition, which takes about as much skill as pumping iron with forklifts. 

   At college meets, an injury, if only mildly maiming, is no reason to quit. 
Only the greenest rookies have no scars on hands and arms. 
Marty Dodge, the coach of the Finger Lakes team, tells how his chain saw once "jumped up" from a log during a contest and laid open his scalp. 
At this year's meet, Ann Thayer, a Colby graduate on the school's alumni team, was just about to complete the twitch-peavey-deck when a teammate drove a peavey point into her hand, breaking a bone and sending her to the hospital. (She was back the next day as a judge.) 

   Ms. Thayer recalls a worse incident, the day the chips hit the fan. 
An ax head flew off, wounding the one good leg of a bystander who was already on crutches. 

   Most of the damage at the meets is to pride, though. 
Pam Parker, a Colby contestant, bursts into tears during the portage event when the wind flips her canoe into a nearby pond and blows it out of reach. 
In a two-man canoe race, University of Vermont woodsmen Albert Knudsen and Bill Cleary launch their canoe on the run and promptly flip over. 
"People who do this make total fools of themselves," says Sally Keefer, a University of Vermont woodswoman. 
"But nobody cares." 

   Woodsmen's meets have camp appeal at schools such as Dartmouth, whose men's team showed up one year in tuxedos for a sawing contest. 
But at Sir Sandford Fleming College of Lindsay, Ontario, where woodsmen's athletics is one of two varsity sports (the other is hockey), students get "woodsmen's fever," a kind of obsessive chopping condition, says Bill Deba, the coach. 
And Finger Lakes college has so many trophies they can't all fit in the display case. 
It worsened its problem this year by winning both the men's and women's grand prizes, edging Sir Sandford Fleming in both cases. 

   Preparing for meets, tool specialists on such teams may spend 30 hours sharpening a single competition saw; the saws are handed down from team to team like Stradivarius violins. 
Some squads train year-round. 
Chuck Congdon of Finger Lakes keeps in shape in the off season by chopping wood for relatives. 
Chris McGee, a passionate young woodsman from Pinkerton Academy in Derry, N.H., is pulling out all the stops for this year's meet; he isn't going to any parties on nights before his events. 

   The ultimate reward for all this work is a chance to win hundreds of dollars at pro woodsmen's meets. 
Mr. Quigley, the part-time pro who competed here on an alumni team, and a teammate showed how good the pros are by sawing through an 8-by-8 pine timber nine times in 39 seconds. 

   But for many, turning pro will remain only a dream. 
Pondering the future with a faraway look in his eyes, Finger Lakes' Mr. Congdon says, "I don't know if I'm good enough for the pros." 

</TEXT>
</DOC>

